00:18:12,960 --> 00:18:21,200
connect is higher. If you really want to actually 
innovate at the edges of communication products,  

189
00:18:21,200 --> 00:18:28,480
you really have to target that cohort that has the 
highest urgency to communicate, and that's teens.

190
00:18:28,480 --> 00:18:33,160
I love that you found these things out, not 
through just research and not through just  

191
00:18:33,160 --> 00:18:38,440
thinking, it was through actual trying things over 
and over and over and trying different audiences,  

192
00:18:38,440 --> 00:18:41,560
trying different experiences. A lot of 
people see your advice and they're like,  

193
00:18:41,560 --> 00:18:45,680
"How does he know?" It's just you've done 
all these things yourself. You've seen them,  

194
00:18:45,680 --> 00:18:50,280
you're sitting there watching teens use these 
apps. I think very few people actually do that,  

195
00:18:50,280 --> 00:18:54,120
and they just come up with these theories 
that aren't based in empirical evidence.

196
00:18:54,800 --> 00:19:01,960
We got pretty good at building these apps. I 
think our first mobile app took us about a year,  

197
00:19:01,960 --> 00:19:08,040
and then our last one took us about two weeks. 
We also got very good at testing apps. The most  

198
00:19:08,040 --> 00:19:14,200
important thing that I often instruct teams to 
do is to develop a reproducible testing process,  

199
00:19:14,200 --> 00:19:21,000
and that will actually influence the probability 
of your success more than anything. It's so  

200
00:19:21,000 --> 00:19:30,320
unpredictable whether a consumer product idea will 
work. If you actually focus more on your process  

201
00:19:30,320 --> 00:19:38,000
for taking many shots at bat, that's what actually 
reduces the risk more than anything. We figured  

202
00:19:38,000 --> 00:19:44,400
out ways to seed apps into schools. We also, 
during the course of that company, we figured out  

203
00:19:44,400 --> 00:19:54,800
how to seed it into affinity groups, hobbyists, 
things like that. We were on app number 15, a lot  

204
00:19:54,800 --> 00:20:04,280
of failures during the course of this company, and 
I remember a lot of our team members were like, "I  

205
00:20:04,280 --> 00:20:11,000
kind of want to leave. I think this is it for me."
One of our key team members actually put in their  

206
00:20:11,000 --> 00:20:19,680
two weeks' notice. The day before we launched our 
final app, we were getting kind of low on money.  

207
00:20:19,680 --> 00:20:30,200
I was tired. I called our lawyer to ask, how do 
you dissolve a company? I messaged a few mentors  

208
00:20:30,200 --> 00:20:38,520
saying like, one people that have been through it, 
and I said, "What are the steps to do this?" Then  

209
00:20:38,520 --> 00:20:44,160
I had a conversation on the way out with that 
team member that wanted to leave, and I said,  

210
00:20:44,160 --> 00:20:52,160
"I understand, but what if the app actually 
starts charting on the App Store?" He said,  

211
00:20:52,160 --> 00:21:03,240
"What are the chances of that? You know that's 
not going to happen." I said, "Sure, okay." We  

212
00:21:03,240 --> 00:21:11,880
launched this app and it was a polling app, tbh, 
and it immediately took off in the school that  

213
00:21:11,880 --> 00:21:18,760
we seeded it into, in Georgia. We picked the 
one school that had the earliest start date in  

214
00:21:18,760 --> 00:21:25,600
the United States because we needed to launch as 
soon as possible, given the state of the company. 

215
00:21:26,400 --> 00:21:33,600
I think it spread to 40% of the school downloaded 
it in the first 24 hours and it rapidly spread to  

216
00:21:33,600 --> 00:21:41,640
the neighboring schools. Suddenly, I was like, 
"Oh, we might have something here." Servers  

217
00:21:41,640 --> 00:21:50,000
started crashing and watching it climb the charts. 
I looked at our numbers and I'm like, "We will  

218
00:21:50,000 --> 00:21:58,760
be number one in the United States in six days." 
Then I looked at our Amazon bill and it was like  

219
00:21:58,760 --> 00:22:04,080
120,000. I looked at our bank account, it 
said 150,000. I'm like, "Okay, these two  

220
00:22:04,080 --> 00:22:11,280
numbers don't really..." I quickly had to put 
together a funding round and I told my team,  

221
00:22:11,280 --> 00:22:16,040
"Can you guys just pause for two months 
and just really focus on this? I think I  

222
00:22:16,040 --> 00:22:21,720
could probably sell this thing." It turned 
into a pretty competitive bidding process,  

223
00:22:21,720 --> 00:22:32,680
actually. There was a really, really great moment 
where there was one of the acquirers, or one of  

224
00:22:32,680 --> 00:22:39,880
the bidders was based in LA, had told me to fly 
down, and they told me to fly down that day. 

225
00:22:39,880 --> 00:22:45,720
I got on a plane, went to the airport without a 
ticket, showed up. When we were rolling out this  

226
00:22:45,720 --> 00:22:53,280
app, we were doing a state-by-state rollout 
strategy where every state was geo-fenced. We  

227
00:22:53,280 --> 00:23:03,880
hadn't launched California until that morning. 
I arrived at this company, this founders in LA's  

228
00:23:03,880 --> 00:23:12,360
house, and he said, "Show me the metrics. You guys 
are like, what? Number four or something?" Since  

229
00:23:12,360 --> 00:23:16,880
we just launched California, it's a big state. I 
said, "No, we're actually number one. We're the  

230
00:23:16,880 --> 00:23:24,560
number one app in the United States." He said, 
"Show me the metrics." Our CTO, Erik Hazzard,  

231
00:23:24,560 --> 00:23:31,480
is a published author in mapping. He created 
an amazing dashboard that could show real-time  

232
00:23:31,480 --> 00:23:37,920
installs on a map. It was around 4:00 PM and 
school had just gotten out, so I zoomed in on the  

233
00:23:37,920 --> 00:23:43,760
block that we were having that meeting, and the 
entire block was lit up with installs all around  

234
00:23:43,760 --> 00:23:53,840
us. Then that's what got the ball rolling on a... 
It was a really, really like, cinematic moment of  

235
00:23:55,520 --> 00:24:02,520
showing something that you created that literally 
just took over the entire neighborhood around you.

236
00:24:02,520 --> 00:24:05,880
That's insane. That's going to 
be in the movie of Nikita Bier  

237
00:24:05,880 --> 00:24:09,320
in the future. A couple of questions 
here. One, you predicted the chart,  

238
00:24:09,320 --> 00:24:12,840
you would hit number one. What does it take 
to hit number one? What is the number you're  

239
00:24:12,840 --> 00:24:16,920
looking at? Is it some number downloads 
to get to number one in the App Store?

240
00:24:16,920 --> 00:24:24,000
It fluctuates. It used to be like 80 to 
100,000 installs, but now you have these  

241
00:24:24,000 --> 00:24:28,720
companies that are just spending extraordinary 
amounts on ads and or injecting it into  

242
00:24:28,720 --> 00:24:33,080
one of their other apps. Between 
Threads, Temu and all these other  

243
00:24:33,080 --> 00:24:40,640
apps that are spending on acquisition and 
all that, some days it's up to 300,000.

244
00:24:40,640 --> 00:24:41,640
That's per day?

245
00:24:41,640 --> 00:24:42,280
Yeah.

246
00:24:42,280 --> 00:24:43,400
Oh, man. Amazing.

247
00:24:43,400 --> 00:24:49,760
At the peak of tbh, we were 
getting 360,000 per day.

248
00:24:49,760 --> 00:24:54,320
The other two things I want to spend a little 
time on here before we move on to the next app is,  

249
00:24:54,320 --> 00:24:57,360
what was the insight that helped you come 
up with this is a big idea that we should  

250
00:24:57,360 --> 00:25:00,386
try? Then what was the insight into how to spread 
this so virally? I know that one is really close.

251
00:25:00,386 --> 00:25:04,640
... to how to spread this so virally, 
and I know that one is really clever.

252
00:25:04,640 --> 00:25:10,680
After building all these apps, we had these 
kind of lingering users that stuck around  

253
00:25:10,680 --> 00:25:16,120
and would share feedback with us on our 
next app. And so there were a couple,  

254
00:25:16,120 --> 00:25:22,480
like there's a senior in high school that I 
would send screenshots of our products. He  

255
00:25:22,480 --> 00:25:27,080
told me about this trend called TBH 
that kids were playing on Snapchat,  

256
00:25:27,080 --> 00:25:33,440
where they would post an image of a 
bunch of emojis and it would say like,  

257
00:25:33,440 --> 00:25:39,360
"I like you. Your smart. Your style is great." 
And you would just reply to the story with the  

258
00:25:39,360 --> 00:25:43,720
emoji of what you felt. And I was like, "This is 
kind of weird. You post this on your story and  

259
00:25:43,720 --> 00:25:52,960
then people send you feedback." And I'm like, "So 
teens are looking for this vehicle for disclosure  

260
00:25:52,960 --> 00:25:58,680
essentially." And I'm like, "That's kind of cool. 
I wonder if you could make that into an app." We  

261
00:25:58,680 --> 00:26:07,160
had sketched some things out. As we were 
sketching things out, I looked on the app store,  

262
00:26:07,160 --> 00:26:13,240
and the number one app in the United States was an 
app called Sarahah. It was for sending anonymous  

263
00:26:13,240 --> 00:26:20,840
messages by adding a link to your Snapchat story.
But the thing that was most interesting was the  

264
00:26:20,840 --> 00:26:28,240
entire app was in Arabic. The number one app in 
the United States was in Arabic. And that was  

265
00:26:28,800 --> 00:26:35,640
one of the most strongest signal that you could 
ever have that people want something. And so when  

266
00:26:35,640 --> 00:26:40,800
I meet with founders, I often tell them like, "The 
way you should be searching for product ideas is  

267
00:26:40,800 --> 00:26:48,120
this concept of latent demand where people are 
trying to obtain a particular value and going  

268
00:26:48,120 --> 00:26:56,120
through a very distortive process to obtain that 
value." And if you can actually crystallize what  

269
00:26:56,120 --> 00:27:04,440
their motivation is and build a product around 
and clear up what they're trying to actually do,  

270
00:27:04,440 --> 00:27:14,120
you can have this kind of intense adoption.
When we saw what people were doing with Sarahah,  

271
00:27:14,120 --> 00:27:18,880
I also looked at some of the tweets and comments 
on it. A lot of people were receiving negative  

272
00:27:18,880 --> 00:27:24,680
messages. And so what I saw with the game 
that kids were playing on Snapchat TBH and  

273
00:27:24,680 --> 00:27:29,840
then Sarahah, I realized just people want to 
know good things about themselves and that they  

274
00:27:29,840 --> 00:27:36,680
don't want these bullying messages that they're 
getting on these anonymous apps, and I was like,  

275
00:27:36,680 --> 00:27:42,840
"Well, what if instead of actually typing what you 
wanted to say about somebody, you just answered  

276
00:27:42,840 --> 00:27:50,040
polls and we authored those polls so that we 
ensured everything would always be positive?" 

277
00:27:51,720 --> 00:27:57,040
I mean, in the back of my head, I always knew 
anonymous apps go viral, but they always lead  

278
00:27:57,040 --> 00:28:02,720
to these awful news stories of kids committing 
suicide, self-harm and all that. And so I was  

279
00:28:02,720 --> 00:28:08,360
like, "I'll never build anything like that." 
But when we came up with this new mechanic  

280
00:28:08,360 --> 00:28:13,680
where you could only say positive things through 
polls, who has the best smile, who's most likely  

281
00:28:13,680 --> 00:28:19,960
to be president, and then you receive it 
as anonymous, but your name is selected,  

282
00:28:19,960 --> 00:28:24,120
what we discovered a couple of things is it 
made users feel a lot better. It actually  

283
00:28:24,120 --> 00:28:30,480
solved what they were trying to do and they 
also sent a much higher volume of messages.  

284
00:28:30,480 --> 00:28:39,000
And so it was literally explosive adoption.
One school I was looking at, they sent 450,000  

285
00:28:39,000 --> 00:28:47,360
messages in the first seven days of adopting it. 
And when you look at day one volume of messages  

286
00:28:47,360 --> 00:28:52,800
sent on a messaging app, you're lucky if 
people send three or four or something,  

287
00:28:52,800 --> 00:29:00,480
but we were sending 60 and we couldn't even 
handle it, so we had to geofence the app  

288
00:29:00,480 --> 00:29:04,680
because we needed to scale our servers, which is 
actually a pretty controversial decision inside  

289
00:29:04,680 --> 00:29:10,640
of our company, because why would you turn 
off something that's working? But at my core,  

290
00:29:10,640 --> 00:29:19,200
I knew if it's working at this many individual 
schools, we could just relaunch it any time and  

291
00:29:19,200 --> 00:29:27,080
it'll go viral. So let's regroup and figure 
out what's happening here and then relaunch.

292
00:29:27,080 --> 00:29:30,640
So you keep talking about how went viral 
and crazy, grew like crazy. I know that  

293
00:29:30,640 --> 00:29:33,960
there's a little trick that you came up with 
to help it spread. Can you just briefly talk  

294
00:29:33,960 --> 00:29:37,280
about what you did there and to help 
it spread so quickly within a school?

295
00:29:37,280 --> 00:29:44,680
I think you're referring to, there's a 
memo that was leaked to BuzzFeed while  

296
00:29:44,680 --> 00:29:52,800
I was at Facebook. The main thing we found 
was like, to be convinced to download an app,  

297
00:29:52,800 --> 00:29:58,040
you need to see it. You need to see the 
marketing message three times or so.  

298
00:29:58,680 --> 00:30:05,920
So you basically need to saturate an area with 
every kind of marketing you can. So we ran ads  

299
00:30:06,720 --> 00:30:13,120
targeted at a particular school to when we 
were seeding and testing these apps. And  

300
00:30:13,120 --> 00:30:19,200
we also followed people creating a dedicated 
Instagram account that went to that school,  

301
00:30:19,200 --> 00:30:25,880
because we learned that high schoolers identify 
their school in their bio, so it says RHS on  

302
00:30:25,880 --> 00:30:33,600
their bio. And so that was how we tried to get 
the entire school to adopt synchronously. We'd  

303
00:30:33,600 --> 00:30:39,160
follow them and then accept the followbacks.
Big misunderstanding though, and I get this DM  

304
00:30:39,160 --> 00:30:43,720
a lot of people are like, "I'm trying to replicate 
your strategy. We've just done it at 15 schools  

305
00:30:43,720 --> 00:30:51,240
and it's not working anymore." This is not the 
way we grew the app. This is how we tested apps.  

306
00:30:53,240 --> 00:30:58,440
Really, it's a little bit nuanced there. That's 
an important nuance because you need to get enough  

307
00:30:58,440 --> 00:31:05,320
intensity of adoption and density for a social 
network to start to get the flywheel spinning,  

308
00:31:05,320 --> 00:31:10,280
but the app should grow by itself after that. And 
people think we just went from school to school  

309
00:31:10,280 --> 00:31:16,280
following every kid on it. You can't, that's 
totally unrealistic. But for the first 100 users,  

310
00:31:16,280 --> 00:31:23,120
yes, that's how we got them. And that allowed us 
to know whether the product was working or not. We  

311
00:31:23,120 --> 00:31:31,960
could get enough people on it and then we could, 
with conviction, say that whether the app had legs  

312
00:31:31,960 --> 00:31:36,800
and we wouldn't have this kind of uncertainty 
like, "Oh, did they add enough friends? Did  

313
00:31:36,800 --> 00:31:41,680
we get enough people on it? Did they reach the 
aha moment because you need friends to get on?" 

314
00:31:41,680 --> 00:31:46,120
So we wanted to eliminate that confounding 
variable, and so we figured out a way to just  

315
00:31:46,120 --> 00:31:51,720
get a bunch of people to adopt at once. And that's 
one thing I encourage a lot of founders to do,  

316
00:31:51,720 --> 00:31:58,760
is figure out a way to eliminate all those 
potentially confounding variables so you can know  

317
00:31:58,760 --> 00:32:03,800
immediately whether something's working or not. 
You never want to walk away from an experiment  

318
00:32:03,800 --> 00:32:11,960
or test and say, "Well, maybe the execution was 
bad because it takes a lot of energy to mobilize  

319
00:32:11,960 --> 00:32:18,560
a team to test something," and you really want 
to make sure your tests actually provide signal.

320
00:32:18,560 --> 00:32:20,960
So your advice here is when 
you're testing something,  

321
00:32:20,960 --> 00:32:24,960
test the best possible version of what 
that could be, whether it takes manual  

322
00:32:24,960 --> 00:32:29,520
work or something that is never going to 
scale, test the ideal. Because that'll  

323
00:32:29,520 --> 00:32:34,080
tell you, " Even if this could be the best 
possible version, do people actually care?"

324
00:32:34,080 --> 00:32:41,840
Yeah, we would try to get an entire school to 
adopt, just to know if everyone had 10 friends,  

325
00:32:42,400 --> 00:32:45,600
would they actually derive value from 
this app? We also did other things,  

326
00:32:46,480 --> 00:32:52,880
and I recommend all companies do this, is 
put live chat customer support in your app  

327
00:32:53,880 --> 00:33:00,000
24 hours a day. It sounds insane. It's like 
the whole point of tech is you don't need to  

328
00:33:00,000 --> 00:33:09,160
do that. That's the whole point of a software. 
But then users get this white glove experience,  

329
00:33:09,160 --> 00:33:14,320
and that eliminates another confounding variable, 
like did they think their problems were solved or  

330
00:33:14,320 --> 00:33:18,840
they were treated well? But most of all, one 
of the reasons I actually recommend people  

331
00:33:18,840 --> 00:33:26,200
put live chat in their app is it's the best 
vehicle for getting feedback and doing user  

332
00:33:26,200 --> 00:33:34,080
research because users will literally tell you 
the problem they're having. So we had our person  

333
00:33:34,080 --> 00:33:38,920
that was running this. He's name is Michael 
Gutierrez. He's done it for all my companies  

334
00:33:38,920 --> 00:33:45,160
actually. He's the community and customer 
support rep. He would paste any interesting  

335
00:33:45,160 --> 00:33:50,840
feedback into Slack and then we would be 
like, "Oh, this user has a great idea. We  

336
00:33:50,840 --> 00:33:55,440
should consider turning that into a feature." 
So you really want your finger on the pulse  

337
00:33:55,440 --> 00:34:02,040
as you roll these things out so you can get a 
sense for what's working, what isn't, and also  

338
00:34:02,040 --> 00:34:09,080
make users feel great and make sure at the end 
they promote your app positively to their peers.

339
00:34:09,080 --> 00:34:15,160
I love that piece of advice.
Okay, so to close out the TBH chapter,  

340
00:34:15,160 --> 00:34:20,120
is there anything else that you think is important 
for people to know or any other lasting lessons  

341
00:34:20,120 --> 00:34:25,080
from that part of your journey that you bring 
with you to new apps that you're building today?

342
00:34:25,080 --> 00:34:31,640
I think the thing that is hard to really 
understand for first-time founders that  

343
00:34:31,640 --> 00:34:43,280
hit breakout success with a consumer product is 
how draining and how spread thin you get, because  

344
00:34:43,280 --> 00:34:52,360
everything breaks. Everything that you built 
needs to be substituted almost every three days. 

345
00:34:53,040 --> 00:34:57,960
I can just give you an example. We were 
just talking about this customer support  

346
00:34:57,960 --> 00:35:04,640
system that we had. The first system broke after 
three days. The next one broke seven days later,  

347
00:35:04,640 --> 00:35:09,640
we had to replace it with a different one that 
could scale even better. And if you think about  

348
00:35:09,640 --> 00:35:17,360
that on every dimension of the company, it is 
absolute chaos to keep the thing online as it  

349
00:35:17,360 --> 00:35:25,440
scales up. And so you have to be ruthless with 
prioritization as something scales up and put  

350
00:35:25,440 --> 00:35:35,880
out the largest fires first, because that was 
something that I didn't really fully understand,  

351
00:35:35,880 --> 00:35:47,000
is how many things go wrong. And if we didn't 
geofence the app, there would be no way we  

352
00:35:47,000 --> 00:35:55,280
would've been able to keep that thing online 
because that gave us some slack to control growth.

353
00:35:55,280 --> 00:35:58,720
This is a good example of when people ask 
like, "Hey, does my app have product-market  

354
00:35:58,720 --> 00:36:02,160
fit?" I think this is an example of this 
is what it looks like when things are  

355
00:36:02,160 --> 00:36:06,280
breaking every three days when you have 
to geofence it to keep it from crashing.

356
00:36:06,280 --> 00:36:15,320
A lot of people ask me like, "What's the benchmark 
for product-market fit?" And this founder that I'm  

357
00:36:15,320 --> 00:36:22,720
friends with, his name's Roger Dickey, he told 
me this one time, "If your product's working,  

358
00:36:22,720 --> 00:36:31,560
you'll know. And if there's any uncertainty, 
it's not working." And it really is a binary  

359
00:36:31,560 --> 00:36:40,480
when it comes to consumer products. People are 
going to be fighting to get into it and you'll  

360
00:36:40,480 --> 00:36:47,320
find new measures that you've never heard of 
like, "Our metric was hourly actives per day."  

361
00:36:47,320 --> 00:36:53,920
Not daily active users, hourly active users. So 
you'll start seeing that and it'll be abundantly  

362
00:36:53,920 --> 00:36:59,840
obvious what product-market fit is. You'll 
know it when you see it is the bottom line.

363
00:36:59,840 --> 00:37:06,000
Okay, so you launch TBH, it goes viral, 
start getting offers from companies. Nine  

364
00:37:06,000 --> 00:37:10,840
weeks later after launch, you end up selling 
it to Facebook. What was it like selling your  

365
00:37:10,840 --> 00:37:15,120
company and then what was it like working 
at Facebook? Which you worked at for four  

366
00:37:15,120 --> 00:37:19,480
years. I was not expecting that when I 
was looking at your LinkedIn. So yeah,  

367
00:37:19,480 --> 00:37:21,880
what was it like selling? What 
was it like working at Facebook?

368
00:37:21,880 --> 00:37:26,320
Selling your company is one of the most draining 
processes you could ever go through as a founder.  

369
00:37:26,320 --> 00:37:36,040
When we met with Facebook, they told me they have 
80 people assigned to this deal. And I'm like,  

370
00:37:36,040 --> 00:37:43,360
I have one person, it's just me. 
