Zay Turner, and he started building it in my 
house and we had tested it to see would this  

554
00:57:14,160 --> 00:57:22,680
new version of tbh actually resonate with kids 
five years later? That was actually the thing  

555
00:57:22,680 --> 00:57:28,040
I wanted to know most of all was like would an 
anonymous polling app actually still be relevant  

556
00:57:28,040 --> 00:57:36,160
five years later? And so we dropped it into the 
school just the same way I've always done it in-

557
00:57:36,160 --> 00:57:38,120
Was it the Georgia School again?

558
00:57:38,120 --> 00:57:47,680
Yes, actually. We launched at the exact same 
school that we launched tbh on the exact same  

559
00:57:47,680 --> 00:57:59,680
day five years later, in fact. And people sent 
a lot of messages, but it wasn't growing. So  

560
00:57:59,680 --> 00:58:09,520
let me pedal back here a bit. So tbh grew through 
variety of things, people sharing their messages  

561
00:58:09,520 --> 00:58:19,280
to Snapchat and text invites, and that was 2017. 
And the way you invited your friends on tbh was  

562
00:58:19,280 --> 00:58:24,960
that you tap their name, your contact name, and 
there was a button that said Invite and then we  

563
00:58:24,960 --> 00:58:30,680
used Twilio to send them a text message. And the 
regulatory environment actually had changed a lot  

564
00:58:30,680 --> 00:58:36,360
over those five years. You really can't send texts 
from a server anymore. It has to be sent from the  

565
00:58:37,000 --> 00:58:43,040
user's device. And just the point of clarification 
is a lot of people clone tbh over the years and  

566
00:58:43,040 --> 00:58:47,320
they think that when you voted on people in 
the polls, it sent them a text. We never did  

567
00:58:47,320 --> 00:58:53,960
that. That's egregiously illegal to do and also 
unethical at a user experience level to send texts  

568
00:58:53,960 --> 00:59:00,560
when people don't even know what's happening.
But anyway, we couldn't send texts over Twilio  

569
00:59:00,560 --> 00:59:08,440
anymore, and that led to people not sending 
as many invites when we created Gas because  

570
00:59:08,440 --> 00:59:15,440
they had to pop the Compose window and hit Send. 
They're going to just tap Invite on five names.  

571
00:59:15,440 --> 00:59:22,160
So we actually had to reinvent all the growth 
systems and it took about I think like nine  

572
00:59:22,160 --> 00:59:31,080
launches including renaming the app, including 
features that just never existed on tbh. So it was  

573
00:59:31,080 --> 00:59:38,680
actually just in many ways like yeah, the concept 
on the surface was the same, but it was very much  

574
00:59:38,680 --> 00:59:47,320
a zero to one development cycle of figuring out 
how to grow this thing again in this climate.

575
00:59:47,320 --> 00:59:49,800
I know that point is really important 
to you. I think a lot of people are like  

576
00:59:49,800 --> 00:59:55,720
Nikita just sold the same app twice. What 
a guy. And the point you're making here is  

577
00:59:56,480 --> 01:00:00,600
not only was the infrastructure completely 
different, the team was different,  

578
01:00:00,600 --> 01:00:05,280
you had to rethink the entire flywheel 
of how it worked and how it grew.

579
01:00:05,280 --> 01:00:12,000
Yeah. And there were so many layers of like we 
validated one thing and then the next thing we  

580
01:00:12,840 --> 01:00:21,640
got stuck on. Like, okay, people send a lot of 
messages. Cool, great. The next thing was will  

581
01:00:21,640 --> 01:00:28,320
it spread within a school? That took us a while 
to get right. Will it hop schools? Each of those  

582
01:00:28,320 --> 01:00:35,920
was a very, very challenging problem in light of 
the new climate that we were operating in. And  

583
01:00:35,920 --> 01:00:44,920
I always do things by the book when it comes to 
operating legally within the compliance framework.  

584
01:00:45,440 --> 01:00:49,680
And that's something when I meet founders and 
they tell me some growth thing that they're doing,  

585
01:00:49,680 --> 01:00:56,320
and I'm like, "You can't do that. That's 
going to cause way more trouble down the line.  

586
01:00:56,320 --> 01:01:02,600
It's going to burn users too." And so we always 
wanted to make it abundantly clear how our growth  

587
01:01:02,600 --> 01:01:07,080
system, how you are inviting friends and all 
that. You can kind of go on a whole diatribe  

588
01:01:07,080 --> 01:01:13,920
on that because the thing that I see a lot of 
founders do is they in the background use user  

589
01:01:13,920 --> 01:01:21,880
data in ways that it shouldn't be used. They 
invite people on your behalf and all that. 

590
01:01:21,880 --> 01:01:28,200
And I have this kind of crazy view that the 
internet is this living and breathing thing.  

591
01:01:28,200 --> 01:01:35,000
There's Wikipedia article called the Gaia 
Hypothesis, which is about biology. And it's  

592
01:01:35,000 --> 01:01:41,560
basically like the earth is kind of living and 
breathing and can respond to threats. Okay? And  

593
01:01:41,560 --> 01:01:48,160
when you enter the rainforest too deep, Ebola 
virus will be released. Okay? So I think the  

594
01:01:48,160 --> 01:01:55,480
internet operates on a similar paradigm here 
where if you do the wrong thing by users,  

595
01:01:55,480 --> 01:02:02,520
the internet will come back and get even and 
defend itself. And so whenever I design products,  

596
01:02:02,520 --> 01:02:08,240
I try to do right by users because it'll 
always come back much worse and I think  

597
01:02:08,240 --> 01:02:14,000
you should always operate above board with how 
you design your growth systems. And with Gas,  

598
01:02:14,000 --> 01:02:22,480
we had to do things the right way and we 
had to figure out at each particular moment  

599
01:02:22,480 --> 01:02:27,960
or problem that we solve, will it spread 
within schools? Will it hop schools? Will  

600
01:02:27,960 --> 01:02:35,800
people pay for it? All of these things was 
a whole reinvention of the original product.

601
01:02:35,800 --> 01:02:39,400
I love that you shared that because I think 
a lot of people see you from the outside and  

602
01:02:39,400 --> 01:02:44,040
they think you're doing all kinds of 
these skeezy growth hacks and making  

603
01:02:44,040 --> 01:02:48,600
teens do things that aren't really mentally 
healthy for them. But it's clear that that's  

604
01:02:48,600 --> 01:02:51,840
the opposite of how you think about it, 
that you're trying to stay very positive,  

605
01:02:51,840 --> 01:02:56,360
like you only allow positive communication. 
You do things that as you just said,  

606
01:02:56,360 --> 01:03:00,800
are going to be good long-term, the internet's 
not going to come and try to shut you down.

607
01:03:00,800 --> 01:03:10,440
The point you bring up here about wanting to 
build a positive thing, some people, sometimes  

608
01:03:10,440 --> 01:03:14,760
I get criticism. It's not actually that often, but 
they say, "Oh, you're building an app that makes  

609
01:03:14,760 --> 01:03:21,120
teens feeling insecure or anything." But with 
Gas, I think we received a message every single  

610
01:03:21,120 --> 01:03:29,600
day from a user telling us that they reconsidered 
suicide or other forms of self-harm. The app sent  

611
01:03:29,600 --> 01:03:36,320
you positive messages and affirmations. It made 
teens feel really good. And I think that is lost  

612
01:03:36,320 --> 01:03:42,920
on a lot of people. Instagram can make you feel 
jealousy and a lot of other social networks are  

613
01:03:42,920 --> 01:03:49,160
a mixed bag in terms of impact. But we were 
entirely focused on making teens feel better. 

614
01:03:49,160 --> 01:03:52,520
And some people might say, "Oh, what if 
someone doesn't get voted for something?"  

615
01:03:52,520 --> 01:03:59,080
We actually built a system to ensure everyone 
got a vote. And what we did was we put your  

616
01:03:59,080 --> 01:04:04,880
name in polls at a higher frequency if you 
weren't being voted on recently. So we wanted  

617
01:04:04,880 --> 01:04:13,520
to spread the love in every way possible, and 
that's what really motivated me to grow this  

618
01:04:13,520 --> 01:04:20,160
thing was watching how it was impacting 10 
million kids in such a short period of time.

619
01:04:20,160 --> 01:04:23,400
I really appreciate you adding that. I didn't know 
all those things about the way you thought about  

620
01:04:23,400 --> 01:04:30,880
these apps. Interestingly, I don't know how much 
you can go into this, but there is a lot of stuff  

621
01:04:30,880 --> 01:04:36,040
going on with Gas around human trafficking and all 
this stuff where people thought people were being  

622
01:04:36,040 --> 01:04:41,480
kidnapped through Gas, which is yeah, talk about 
that whatever you can because that's pretty crazy.

623
01:04:41,480 --> 01:04:48,440
We had this hoax started where people were 
saying the app was used for human trafficking.  

624
01:04:48,440 --> 01:04:55,640
And I was like, "This is so strange." This is 
a anonymous polling app without messaging and  

625
01:04:57,280 --> 01:05:02,520
the only thing you could do is send compliments 
to your friends. And I researched into it and I  

626
01:05:02,520 --> 01:05:10,000
saw that this is actually plaguing a lot of 
apps and any app that has gone viral in any  

627
01:05:10,000 --> 01:05:14,280
way has actually had this hoax started. 
And part of the reason it happens is it  

628
01:05:15,280 --> 01:05:21,360
gets you attention if you say that about 
an app. As a teenager, if you say, "Oh,  

629
01:05:21,360 --> 01:05:25,640
this app is dangerous," and then you get a bunch 
of followers and who doesn't love followers?  

630
01:05:26,400 --> 01:05:31,720
So it's actually a really viral piece of 
content if you put it out. And so we had  

631
01:05:31,720 --> 01:05:36,320
this hoax started and we were like, "This could 
kill the company." And I talked to a bunch of  

632
01:05:36,320 --> 01:05:40,440
founders that it happened to them and they said, 
"Yeah, we had to shut down because of that."

633
01:05:40,440 --> 01:05:40,960
Wow.

634
01:05:40,960 --> 01:05:51,880
And I was like, "Is this it? Is this the 
end of the company?" And I remember it hit  

635
01:05:51,880 --> 01:05:59,560
number one when we started getting a few of these 
reports in our support channels. And I was like,  

636
01:05:59,560 --> 01:06:03,440
"I'm just going to plant the flag on posts that 
we hit number one in the App Store because this  

637
01:06:03,440 --> 01:06:07,440
thing's probably going to shut down soon." 
So I make this announcement on Twitter,  

638
01:06:07,440 --> 01:06:13,600
"I just made the number one app and I thought it 
would just be dead in a week." And then I just had  

639
01:06:13,600 --> 01:06:18,200
this sudden burst of energy and I was like, 
"I'm going to win. I'm going to fight this.  

640
01:06:18,200 --> 01:06:25,000
This is not true. It makes no sense at all."
And so we fought it at every vector possible,  

641
01:06:25,000 --> 01:06:31,360
this completely made up hoax. We met with 
journalists, reporters to make sure that  

642
01:06:31,360 --> 01:06:37,360
the number one match every time you search Gas 
app human trafficking was Gas app is not for  

643
01:06:37,360 --> 01:06:42,600
human trafficking. And so that ended up being 
The Washington Post headline. We insisted that  

644
01:06:42,600 --> 01:06:46,760
that be the headline if we do the interview. So 
that was the first thing that showed up on Google  

645
01:06:46,760 --> 01:06:52,120
anytime someone searched it. There were schools 
and even a police station that posted that this  

646
01:06:52,120 --> 01:06:57,680
app is used for human trafficking. I called those 
superintendents, I called those police chiefs  

647
01:06:57,680 --> 01:07:04,000
and have got them to publicly retract it. And we 
had some of the reviews on the App Store. We asked  

648
01:07:04,000 --> 01:07:09,400
Apple to remove them because we got review bombed.
But the thing that actually was the most impactful  

649
01:07:09,400 --> 01:07:16,880
was my girlfriend made a video, a TikTok video 
explaining that it's not true. And anytime someone  

650
01:07:16,880 --> 01:07:22,280
deleted their account, they could watch this 
video explaining it's not true. And at the peak,  

651
01:07:22,280 --> 01:07:30,840
we had 3% of users deleting their accounts per 
day. So it was like a catastrophe for an app  

652
01:07:30,840 --> 01:07:39,800
and we got it down to 0.1% through relentless, 
relentless effort. And it was really just an  

653
01:07:39,800 --> 01:07:48,800
unusual thing that happens when you grow really 
fast is this human trafficking hoax that starts.  

654
01:07:48,800 --> 01:07:55,600
And you don't understand how crazy it is until 
it happens to your company, but it was kind  

655
01:07:55,600 --> 01:08:01,320
of hilarious to think about. This app was the 
most harmless benign thing you could think of.

656
01:08:01,320 --> 01:08:05,200
This is insane. I did not know this full 
story. And you were doing all this while  

657
01:08:05,200 --> 01:08:09,160
you were trying to scale the app and trying 
to keep the servers up and try to grow it,  

658
01:08:09,160 --> 01:08:12,800
right? What was that like to try 
to manage all these things at once?

659
01:08:12,800 --> 01:08:20,520
I was sleeping three hours a day for three 
months. It was extraordinarily difficult to  

660
01:08:20,520 --> 01:08:27,440
do it all. Our team was also relentless though. 
They would come over to my house 9:00 a.m. stay  

661
01:08:27,440 --> 01:08:35,760
until midnight and just do that seven days a 
week. So yeah, it was definitely one of the  

662
01:08:35,760 --> 01:08:44,640
most physically draining things ever, but we were 
just so tactical. I remember investors were asking  

663
01:08:44,640 --> 01:08:51,040
to meet with us and I said, "If you can't get 
a celebrity to post that this isn't true, then  

664
01:08:51,800 --> 01:08:59,800
we're not interested." But yeah, we went after 
it on every vector and it ended up being okay.

665
01:08:59,800 --> 01:09:04,600
I love how you took your brain to this 
other completely different problem and  

666
01:09:04,600 --> 01:09:09,320
thought about all the levers you could use 
to change the conversation around the app.

667
01:09:09,320 --> 01:09:14,720
Yeah. I remember we had these TikTok videos 
that were made that were saying it was true  

668
01:09:14,720 --> 01:09:22,280
and I networked my way all the way to the CEO 
of TikTok and I said, "Can you delete these?"  

669
01:09:22,280 --> 01:09:31,320
And we got this information deleted. Yeah, so 
it was really a whole new test of our team's  

670
01:09:31,320 --> 01:09:36,320
capacities was fighting. The key thing that 
you have to know though when you have a hoax  

671
01:09:36,320 --> 01:09:41,840
spreading about your app is you really have 
to make sure the hoax is less viral than your  

672
01:09:41,840 --> 01:09:48,880
app. And at a few points, the hoax was more 
viral than our app and we had to take this-

673
01:09:48,880 --> 01:09:50,580
The K-factor of the hoax.

674
01:09:50,580 --> 01:09:51,400
Yeah.

675
01:09:51,400 --> 01:09:58,080
That's absurd. Okay. So broadly, you built this 
app. Again, a big success. I saw a stat that  

676
01:09:58,080 --> 01:10:03,760
you made $11 million in sales through the 
app, 10 million downloads. Is that right?

677
01:10:03,760 --> 01:10:11,080
Yeah. It was a blowout success in terms 
of like it grew bigger than tbh. We  

678
01:10:11,080 --> 01:10:17,360
monetized it. We ran almost entirely on 
startup credits, so it was basically-

679
01:10:17,360 --> 01:10:19,920
Like Cloud Credits? Like AWS Credits?

680
01:10:19,920 --> 01:10:27,680
Yeah. AWS Credits, Mixpanel. I remember when I 
saw the early data, I'm like, "Okay, now it's  

681
01:10:27,680 --> 01:10:34,480
time for me to negotiate every bill down to the 
last cent of margin for every vendor." And I got  

682
01:10:34,480 --> 01:10:41,720
credits everywhere, and so we really were tactical 
with that. And so we ended up being all just pure  

683
01:10:41,720 --> 01:10:50,120
cashflow for the team. We had no investors. And it 
was just so interesting though that the way that  

684
01:10:50,120 --> 01:10:58,320
I started posting about it on Twitter was it kind 
of captured the zeitgeist of the internet. And we  

685
01:10:58,320 --> 01:11:02,560
didn't intend on selling it. We were just going to 
let this thing run its course and just be this app  

686
01:11:02,560 --> 01:11:09,720
that kind of lives in the background of our lives. 
But once it started capturing the zeitgeist of  

687
01:11:09,720 --> 01:11:14,240
Twitter, I was like, "Wait a minute, we could 
probably sell this thing." And that's when we  

688
01:11:14,240 --> 01:11:20,840
started engaging with some of these, we ended 
up getting three companies that wanted to buy  

689
01:11:20,840 --> 01:11:29,800
it. I won't be able to say them, but ultimately we 
ended up selling to Discord and we joined Discord.

690
01:11:29,800 --> 01:11:35,920
Awesome. So before we move on to the next part of 
the journey and some of the other insights that I  

691
01:11:35,920 --> 01:11:41,240
want to get into, is there any lasting lessons 
that you took away from Gas as a product that  

692
01:11:41,240 --> 01:11:46,040
you take with you to advising startups in terms of 
building the product design? I know there's many,  

693
01:11:46,040 --> 01:11:50,000
but any that stand out most that you 
think are really interesting to share?

694
01:11:50,000 --> 01:11:55,440
I think I kind of touched on this before, which 
was trying to validate things in a sequence  

695
01:11:55,440 --> 01:12:00,920
of like, will people use the core flow? Will 
people spread it within their peer group?  

696
01:12:00,920 --> 01:12:07,120
Will it hop peer groups? And what I think the 
most important thing that I learned is that's  

697
01:12:07,120 --> 01:12:13,440
actually a really great way to do zero to one 
product development is execute at 100% for the  

698
01:12:13,440 --> 01:12:18,760
thing you're trying to validate at that specific 
stage of the product development cycle. And then  

699
01:12:19,880 --> 01:12:25,160
you can kind of half-ass the rest just so 
you can get 100% signal on that one part. 

700
01:12:25,680 --> 01:12:29,480
And so we made the polling experience 
just perfect. The questions were great.  

701
01:12:30,000 --> 01:12:34,960
Push notifications, everything worked. And 
then the next stage was getting sharing and  

702
01:12:34,960 --> 01:12:40,200
virality working. And so compartmentalizing 
those things because ultimately you'll have  

703
01:12:40,200 --> 01:12:43,640
too much scope creep if you try to solve 
everything at once and validate. And also  

704
01:12:43,640 --> 01:12:48,080
you're not going to get signal too, like you're 
trying to test one thing at a time. So the way  

705
01:12:48,080 --> 01:12:52,320
that now I approach a lot of consumer 
product development is if this is true,  

706
01:12:52,320 --> 01:12:56,280
then what next needs to be true for this thing 
to work out? And these layers of conditional  

707
01:12:56,280 --> 01:13:01,640
statements. And the more layers you have, the 
higher risk your product is, so you should try  

708
01:13:01,640 --> 01:13:06,640
to condense it to about like four things 
that must be true for the thing to work.

709
01:13:06,640 --> 01:13:09,400
And this comes back to your advice of 
the thing you need to get good at is  

710
01:13:09,400 --> 01:13:13,000
testing and learning and making it really quick.

711
01:13:13,000 --> 01:13:13,600
Yeah.

712
01:13:13,600 --> 01:13:16,640
Okay. Maybe one last thing along this 
thread. I'm just really curious how  

713
01:13:16,640 --> 01:13:20,080
this hoax came to be, like who's 
behind it? How does this happen?

714
01:13:20,080 --> 01:13:30,440
We got a original support message, which was 
a screenshot of a story on Snapchat and it  

715
01:13:30,440 --> 01:13:37,280
said, "Do not download the Gas app. It's for human 
trafficking." Okay? And it was a screenshot that  

716
01:13:37,280 --> 01:13:44,160
had like that mirror effect where you have 
like 10 people that screenshotted it. More,  

717
01:13:44,160 --> 01:13:52,240
like 40 people because it had all the usernames. 
So I was looking at this and I'm like, "How many  

718
01:13:52,240 --> 01:13:58,960
people have seen this?" And it looked like a viral 
thing on Snapchat. And then I went to the App  

719
01:13:58,960 --> 01:14:08,000
Store page and I saw a review that said this app 
is for human trafficking. And I went to my team  

720
01:14:08,000 --> 01:14:18,480
and I said, "This will probably kill the company. 
This will kill the product. I've seen this before  

721
01:14:18,480 --> 01:14:25,520
with consumer apps and it's evident to me this is 
going to be 10 times bigger tomorrow." And they  

722
01:14:25,520 --> 01:14:29,080
were like, "No. It's just one message. What do you 
mean?" I'm like, "No, no, it's been screenshotted  

723
01:14:29,080 --> 01:14:35,520
40 times and now it's on the App Store page." 
And we got another message four hours later. 

724
01:14:35,520 --> 01:14:42,360
And the next day, it was our entire App 
Store page was just covered with reviews  

725
01:14:42,360 --> 01:14:48,240
saying that the app's for human trafficking. 
And we actually had to rebrand the app. We  

726
01:14:48,240 --> 01:14:56,240
relaunched it once and we're like, "Let's just 
call it something different. Just relaunch it on  

727
01:14:56,240 --> 01:15:03,305
the other side of the country." We did that, 
started going viral again. And the craziest-

728
01:15:03,305 --> 01:15:11,040
... again. And the craziest thing was it 
re-emerged and what happened was one user was  

729
01:15:11,040 --> 01:15:17,600
friends with another person in another state and 
they got an invitation. And that user told them,  

730
01:15:17,600 --> 01:15:20,960
"Oh, that was in my state. It's actually 
for human trafficking." And then it just  

731
01:15:20,960 --> 01:15:26,520
completely started again and then it 
was too late at that point to relaunch  

732
01:15:26,520 --> 01:15:33,480
again. We just realized, " We got to 
fight this thing." And ultimately,  

733
01:15:33,480 --> 01:15:46,080
I don't think we'll ever know the true origin, but 
it was definitely a living, breathing like hoax.

734
01:15:46,080 --> 01:15:50,120
That is insane. The story just gets more 
and more interesting. What were some of  

735
01:15:50,120 --> 01:15:52,600
the previous names, by the way? 
Is that something you can share?

736
01:15:52,600 --> 01:15:59,320
Yeah, we went through a bunch. One of them 
was called Crush, one of them was called Melt,  

737
01:15:59,320 --> 01:16:04,080
and another was... The interesting thing 
about Crush is we got a great domain. We  

738
01:16:04,080 --> 01:16:12,160
thought this would be the name. This was between 
some of the re-brands. We tested it and we saw  

739
01:16:12,160 --> 01:16:16,760
that invitations dropped significantly 
under the Crush name and we were like,  

740
01:16:16,760 --> 01:16:21,840
"What's going on here?" And we found that 
actually when you invite someone to an app,  

741
01:16:21,840 --> 01:16:29,320
regardless of the app, you generally... Boys 
invite boys, girls invite girls to apps. And  

742
01:16:29,320 --> 01:16:35,320
boys didn't want to invite their friends 
to an app called Crush with a pink icon. 

743
01:16:35,320 --> 01:16:39,800
And then we looked at the data and 
the app. I mean this was true TBH too,  

744
01:16:39,800 --> 01:16:46,040
which was the app indexed about 60 to 65% women. 
So we were just like, "Let's make the app more  

745
01:16:46,040 --> 01:16:51,960
masculine and see what happens. We need balance 
on this." So we made the icon black with a flame,  

746
01:16:51,960 --> 01:16:59,360
called it Gas and the invites rate jumped. And 
you think a name doesn't matter, but right at  

747
01:16:59,360 --> 01:17:07,160
the moment of sending an invite... So that was one 
of the interesting insights on the naming process.

748
01:17:07,160 --> 01:17:11,600
Man, there's just endless stories that we could 
keep getting into, but we've also gone very long,  

749
01:17:11,600 --> 01:17:16,440
so I'm going to try to move on to another 
topic. So I ask people on Twitter what to  

750
01:17:16,440 --> 01:17:21,520
ask you? Just that question got a thousand 
likes just me asking, "What should I ask  

751
01:17:21,520 --> 01:17:25,840
Nikita?" And the most common question, I'm sure 
you get this a lot, is just people wondering,  

752
01:17:25,840 --> 01:17:30,320
do you ever want to build a durable consumer app? 
Is it possible to build a durable consumer app? 

753
01:17:30,320 --> 01:17:35,440
Scott Belsky asked this, Robert at Figma asked 
this, and Scott actually had a really nice way  

754
01:17:35,440 --> 01:17:41,360
of describing it about why are so many quick 
sensation consumer apps proving to be more akin  

755
01:17:41,360 --> 01:17:46,160
to summer songs than enduring standalone products 
and businesses? So there's kind of two questions  

756
01:17:46,160 --> 01:17:54,400
here. One is, do you aim to build a durable 
consumer app? And two, how possible is it?

757
01:17:54,400 --> 01:18:05,840
A lot of the fundamental tools for communicating 
with our friends either messaging or broadcasting  

758
01:18:05,840 --> 01:18:14,080
one-to-many like on stories or the incumbents 
have built pretty large motes in terms of  

759
01:18:14,080 --> 01:18:22,840
network effects and to provide true an 
order of magnitude better experience is  

760
01:18:22,840 --> 01:18:26,000
non-trivial because they've been actually 
improving these products so much over the  

761
01:18:26,000 --> 01:18:33,160
years and there's not that many entry points.
Not to say that it's not impossible. Snapchat  

762
01:18:33,160 --> 01:18:40,360
was showed that there was style of messaging that 
people wanted that the incumbents weren't serving.  

763
01:18:40,360 --> 01:18:45,360
But I think there's these kind of edges that 
you can go after with a much higher probability  

764
01:18:45,360 --> 01:18:51,200
of success and they might not actually be 
something that's durable necessarily. And  

765
01:18:51,200 --> 01:18:59,120
I think finding durability for a communication 
or social product, that's a black swan event.  

766
01:19:00,520 --> 01:19:08,840
Retention for consumer social is there's a 
tremendous amount of randomness. There's one  

767
01:19:08,840 --> 01:19:15,520
every decade. If it was simple, I would 
just be printing $1 trillion companies. 

768
01:19:15,520 --> 01:19:21,800
I be printing Facebook's every time I sat down. 
But I think it's actually a lot of it is pure  

769
01:19:21,800 --> 01:19:28,240
randomness. On the other hand, growing a 
product can be a science. With certainty,  

770
01:19:28,240 --> 01:19:35,600
if you're good at your job, you can make an 
app grow and go viral. Now why haven't I tried  

771
01:19:35,600 --> 01:19:42,240
to take the viral part and build something 
that has been durable or long-lasting? I'll  

772
01:19:42,240 --> 01:19:47,840
tell you a little bit about my motivations. My 
favorite part about product development is you  

773
01:19:47,840 --> 01:19:54,480
make this thing through the night. You build 
it and you watch it take over the internet. 

774
01:19:54,480 --> 01:20:02,160
That is the most thrilling drug I think you could 
ever experience. And just watching it spread all  

775
01:20:02,160 --> 01:20:11,160
over the country is like you drop an app in the 
deep south in Georgia and then you look on your  

776
01:20:11,160 --> 01:20:17,200
analytics dashboard and 40% of the high school 
down your street in Los Angeles has downloaded  

777
01:20:17,200 --> 01:20:23,280
it one week later. That's a really profound 
feeling. It's crazy to have that sort of impact  

778
01:20:23,280 --> 01:20:31,560
as a three-person team, and I live for that.
When I joined Facebook, here's an interesting  

779
01:20:31,560 --> 01:20:37,400
connection. So I joined Facebook and I saw 
that many of my peers were looking up to VPs  

780
01:20:37,400 --> 01:20:42,960
and they're like, "That's what I want to make it 
to one day. I want to run a large organization. I  

781
01:20:42,960 --> 01:20:50,040
want to have lots of reports." And then I met 
with VPs and they were actually jealous of me  

782
01:20:50,040 --> 01:20:58,280
because my quality of life was actually pretty 
cool. I got to build something high impact that  

783
01:20:58,280 --> 01:21:04,320
made many teens feel better about themselves, 
made a decent amount of money. And then I wasn't  

784
01:21:05,320 --> 01:21:10,600
in charge of this becoming a people manager that 
has to run this large organization for many years. 

785
01:21:11,600 --> 01:21:21,880
I think one day I will run maybe a venture scale 
business, but I will say that I kind of like the  

786
01:21:21,880 --> 01:21:27,600
way that I've been doing things so far in terms 
of quality of life and being fun. Financially,  

787
01:21:27,600 --> 01:21:33,680
it's been great. So I think that 
part is what motivates me. And yeah,  

788
01:21:33,680 --> 01:21:40,680
I don't think running a large corporation 
is necessarily what I described as fun.

789
01:21:40,680 --> 01:21:45,320
That's amazing, man. I am really happy we 
went here. So much of this resonates with  

790
01:21:45,320 --> 01:21:50,880
the way I think. And obviously, a big part of 
this is also just it's very hard, as you said,  

791
01:21:50,880 --> 01:21:56,520
to build a consumer app that grows first 
of all. Second, that actually lasts. But  

792
01:21:56,520 --> 01:22:03,520
that is interesting that you do hope to 
one day build a venture funded business.

793
01:22:03,520 --> 01:22:10,360
I mean TBH was venture backed, but I just 
don't... I think I'm going to have to...  

794
01:22:10,360 --> 01:22:14,000
Do I want to sign up for 10 years? 
And if you actually look at some of  

795
01:22:14,000 --> 01:22:21,360
the numbers on the actual proceeds that 
some of these founders get after an IPO,  

796
01:22:21,360 --> 01:22:26,920
after seven rounds of dilution, a lot of 
them are pretty comparable to what we get  

797
01:22:26,920 --> 01:22:36,160
from our apps for 90 days of work. So yeah, 
the trade-offs there are pretty faithful.

798
01:22:36,160 --> 01:22:38,800
Actually, just on that note, so what 
would make you actually decide to  

799
01:22:38,800 --> 01:22:41,840
go venture funded? You talked about 
how if you're going more mainstream,  

800
01:22:41,840 --> 01:22:47,480
non-teens folks after 22 years old, 
is that why you would go that route?

801
01:22:47,480 --> 01:22:59,560
I don't think that it's necessarily that part. 
I think if I could keep the team lean and scale  

802
01:22:59,560 --> 01:23:07,480
up... I think there's some actual founders 
that actually operate very lean teams and  

803
01:23:07,480 --> 01:23:13,800
have reached very large scale in terms of the 
valuations of the company. Actually the most  

804
01:23:13,800 --> 01:23:18,680
iconic example is Elon Musk. His teams are 
actually pretty thin overall and he's in the  

805
01:23:18,680 --> 01:23:26,080
weeds doing product development. And so I think, 
yeah, if I was to ever do it, I would do it under  

806
01:23:26,080 --> 01:23:33,880
very specific set of operating principles 
versus turning it into a big tech company.

807
01:23:33,880 --> 01:23:39,680
Queue investor is emailing you right 
now with term sheets. Okay. Nikita,  

808
01:23:39,680 --> 01:23:44,120
this has been amazing. There's one last segment 
I want to spend a little time on, which is just  

809
01:23:44,120 --> 01:23:49,840
kind of a rapid fire of pieces of advice you've 
shared that I think is incredibly insightful about  

810
01:23:49,840 --> 01:23:54,520
how to build a successful consumer app. And 
so I'm thinking I'll just go through three to  

811
01:23:54,520 --> 01:23:59,320
five and see what you think and see what you 
can add to the advice. How does that sound?

812
01:23:59,320 --> 01:24:00,400
Sounds great.

813
01:24:00,400 --> 01:24:05,040
Okay, cool. So the first is just 
contact permissions in iOS 18  

814
01:24:05,040 --> 01:24:09,480
changes the game and how people can grow 
apps basically makes it harder to invite  

815
01:24:09,480 --> 01:24:14,920
your friends. Thoughts on how people should 
be thinking about this in their products.

816
01:24:15,560 --> 01:24:18,674
When I first saw it, I was really concerned.

817
01:24:18,674 --> 01:24:23,000
I saw your tweet about it. You're 
like, "That's the end. Game over."

818
01:24:23,000 --> 01:24:27,760
Just let me frame things up for 
you. The contact permissions screen,  

819
01:24:27,760 --> 01:24:35,160
you average about 65% approval rate across all 
apps. It's higher for teens, lower for adults,  

820
01:24:36,680 --> 01:24:43,360
but if you have a 65% consenting to contacts 
access, then the next step on this new iOS  

821
01:24:43,360 --> 01:24:49,600
18 change is you select which contacts you 
want to allow the app to access. And it's  

822
01:24:49,600 --> 01:24:55,320
an alphabetical list. And that alphabetical 
list for me, I have 550 contacts or something. 

823
01:24:55,320 --> 01:25:02,760
The first 10 contacts are punctuation symbols 
from whatever dirty entry I put when I was  

824
01:25:02,760 --> 01:25:07,440
driving or something. So you have to scroll 
down and find that name. So I have to find  

825
01:25:07,440 --> 01:25:15,400
Lenny. I have to add you. And what if you're not 
an app user? So I just added you or three others.  

826
01:25:16,000 --> 01:25:22,400
Assuming users are willing to even do that. 
You and then the three others never sign up,  

827
01:25:22,400 --> 01:25:25,520
but maybe three of your friends do.
But I never get connected to them  

828
01:25:25,520 --> 01:25:35,040
because there's no over... So my expectation is 
it's going to be very difficult to find friends  

829
01:25:35,040 --> 01:25:40,600
on apps going forward to invite friends on 
apps going forward. And that founders will  

830
01:25:40,600 --> 01:25:49,760
need to rethink how they do it. And of the 
companies, I'm working with on intro, we are  

831
01:25:49,760 --> 01:25:57,760
looking at ways to reinvent what contact sync is 
or what purpose it served. It's not promising,  

832
01:25:57,760 --> 01:26:06,200
but we have some good leads and I think we'll have 
a whole new set of apps emerging as a consequence.  

833
01:26:06,200 --> 01:26:14,640
But if you're betting on contact sync as a company 
right now, you better start thinking about plan B.

834
01:26:14,640 --> 01:26:19,200
So what I take away here is just it is now 
much different and there's an opportunity  

835
01:26:19,200 --> 01:26:23,360
to think of something really clever that would 
give you a huge advantage if you can crack it.

836
01:26:23,360 --> 01:26:29,040
Yes, but most likely I think most apps will 
not have social graphs going forward and this  

837
01:26:29,040 --> 01:26:34,800
will entrench incumbents even more. I don't 
think Apple acknowledged that. I think the  

838
01:26:34,800 --> 01:26:41,640
person that designed the feature probably 
has never built an app or done contact  

839
01:26:41,640 --> 01:26:48,000
sync before because the flow is egregiously 
bad and it doesn't actually even, I think,  

840
01:26:48,000 --> 01:26:53,640
benefit the user's privacy because it just 
completely eliminates the feature altogether.

841
01:26:53,640 --> 01:26:59,960
Okay, next topic. So you helped this product 
called Dupe succeed. It's doing incredibly  

842
01:26:59,960 --> 01:27:03,480
well from what I can see. And I saw you 
tweet about one of the key things that  

843
01:27:03,480 --> 01:27:07,560
you helped them through, which is 
to invert, I'm reading this quote,  

844
01:27:07,560 --> 01:27:13,280
"Inverting the time to value so that the user 
experience is the aha moment in seconds." Talk  

845
01:27:13,280 --> 01:27:17,880
about that insight and how important that is 
to building a successful consumer social app.

846
01:27:17,880 --> 01:27:22,240
This kind of concept of getting users to the 
aha moment is something I recurringly bring  

847
01:27:22,240 --> 01:27:30,320
up to every company I work with. And you have to 
understand that in 2024, people's attention spans  

848
01:27:30,320 --> 01:27:37,440
are like three seconds. It's really sad, but we 
are spread thin through so many notifications,  

849
01:27:37,440 --> 01:27:42,760
products, everything that if you can't 
demonstrate value in the first three seconds,  

850
01:27:42,760 --> 01:27:46,960
it's over. And this also leads back to the 
contact sync question that you talked about  

851
01:27:46,960 --> 01:27:52,120
was you have to sign up and then the first night 
you have to see all of your friends on the app and  

852
01:27:52,120 --> 01:27:58,880
experience it, otherwise you'll churn.
So this idea of inverting the value,  

853
01:27:58,880 --> 01:28:02,960
when I was working with Dupe, they had this kind 
of shopping app that had a bunch of different  

854
01:28:02,960 --> 01:28:08,560
features and there was one feature that I saw that 
was interesting called Deal Hop and it allowed you  

855
01:28:08,560 --> 01:28:16,120
to just put in a product page and it would find 
the cheapest version of it online. Something  

856
01:28:16,120 --> 01:28:24,120
I already do through a bunch of duct taped 
methods of Google image search, Google Lens. And  

857
01:28:24,640 --> 01:28:31,320
I was like, "That should be a whole company. 
But how are we going to teach users to do it  

858
01:28:31,320 --> 01:28:37,880
and how do we expose them to that aha moment 
as fast as possible in a memorable iconic way?" 

859
01:28:38,520 --> 01:28:43,960
I had this product I built a while back where you 
just type the domain in front of an existing URL.  

860
01:28:43,960 --> 01:28:51,080
So I told them, "You should try this. It's very 
marketable, but you need to get a very short  

861
01:28:51,080 --> 01:28:55,760
domain that matches what you're doing." And so 
he went out and bought Dupe.com for I don't know  

862
01:28:55,760 --> 01:29:02,120
how much, but when he bought that I was pretty 
excited. I'm like, well, if this doesn't work,  

863
01:29:02,120 --> 01:29:05,520
I'm going to feel terrible, but if it does 
work, it's going to be a blowout success. 

864
01:29:05,520 --> 01:29:12,680
So we put out a couple videos about it and then 
it was iconic, went viral, the videos. Users  

865
01:29:12,680 --> 01:29:19,560
remembered to do it, to type dupe.com in front 
of a URL. Now I think they're making millions  

866
01:29:19,560 --> 01:29:28,640
in ARR in a matter, and I think under 60 days of 
launching. And that was a blowout success. And of  

867
01:29:28,640 --> 01:29:35,360
the companies I work with, I would say it happens 
about 50% of the time we hit that much success,  

868
01:29:35,360 --> 01:29:41,600
but we hit success. I think 50% of the time it's 
outright failure because consumer is so random.

869
01:29:41,600 --> 01:29:46,640
And so what I'm hearing is a big 
insight is just ideally get to  

870
01:29:46,640 --> 01:29:49,920
three seconds time to value. Is that the advice?

871
01:29:49,920 --> 01:29:50,480
Yeah.

872
01:29:52,240 --> 01:29:54,040
Sounds great. Easy peasy.

873
01:29:55,120 --> 01:30:01,480
Yeah. You really have to craft 
onboarding everything to ensure  

874
01:30:01,480 --> 01:30:11,720
that that's where the design part comes 
in of being a great product person.

875
01:30:11,720 --> 01:30:15,000
I imagine a big part of this is just cutting 
things you think... Like killing your darlings,  

876
01:30:15,000 --> 01:30:20,280
cutting things you think people need and 
just being really ruthless with that,.

877
01:30:20,280 --> 01:30:30,480
Really ruthless, but also being extraordinarily 
creative with how you use the tools available to  

878
01:30:30,480 --> 01:30:38,360
activate a user. I think extraordinary product 
people are deeply aware of every possible API  

879
01:30:38,360 --> 01:30:45,000
and how it can be used in non-traditional ways. 
Like this URL trick was something that I think  

880
01:30:45,720 --> 01:30:54,040
was non-traditional that people adopted very 
quickly. I have a whole laundry list of iOS  

881
01:30:54,040 --> 01:30:59,480
mechanisms that people use for a certain 
way today, but you could invert them. 

882
01:30:59,480 --> 01:31:03,160
Contact sync is a great example because you 
sync your contacts and then it finds all the  

883
01:31:03,160 --> 01:31:07,400
friends and then ranks the people who are not 
on the app yet but have a bunch of friends  

884
01:31:07,400 --> 01:31:17,080
on it. So there's a bunch of ways that you can 
one tap, expose a ton of value to users that I  

885
01:31:17,080 --> 01:31:24,160
think founders often neglect. A lot of founders 
will go and say, "Oh, they can just exchange  

886
01:31:24,160 --> 01:31:29,720
usernames and that's how they can add each other."
That is the most unrealistic thing ever because  

887
01:31:29,720 --> 01:31:35,560
that means you have to see the username, type it 
into the app. You have to do that what 50 times to  

888
01:31:35,560 --> 01:31:45,400
get a 50-person friend list. So we're looking 
at 10,000 taps versus one. So that's what I  

889
01:31:45,400 --> 01:31:52,960
mean by trying to get people to the activation 
moment, the aha moment and get them to value.

890
01:31:52,960 --> 01:31:57,720
I love that advice. So maybe as just a last 
question along these lines. When you come to  

891
01:31:57,720 --> 01:32:04,400
a founder, a relationship that you're a startup, 
you're trying to help, is there one more thing  

892
01:32:04,400 --> 01:32:09,360
that you find often ends up being really helpful 
to them? Any common piece of advice that's like,  

893
01:32:09,360 --> 01:32:13,800
"Oh, this is probably what's going to help 
you." You talked about this aha moment step,  

894
01:32:13,800 --> 01:32:17,160
the contact sharing stuff. I guess is 
there anything else that's just like  

895
01:32:17,160 --> 01:32:20,240
this is something that's probably 
going to help you with your app?

896
01:32:20,240 --> 01:32:28,960
Right now, I think I advise around 35, 36 
companies and all of them are at different  

897
01:32:28,960 --> 01:32:36,760
stages of challenges they're facing. Some of 
them are pure at the product concept stage.  

898
01:32:36,760 --> 01:32:44,160
Some of them are venture backed billion-dollar 
companies and each of them faces different  

899
01:32:44,160 --> 01:32:52,880
problems. The first thing I often do is I ask 
them to show me the analytics. We look at how  

900
01:32:52,880 --> 01:32:59,240
people are distributing the app today, what is 
the milestone that a user must hit to become  

901
01:32:59,240 --> 01:33:07,520
activated and what's getting in the way of that?
I also take a very deep look at every funnel  

902
01:33:07,520 --> 01:33:19,040
that users come through. And I think a lot of 
founders separate marketing and product growth,  

903
01:33:19,040 --> 01:33:23,760
like top of funnel growth from the 
actual products growth mechanisms, but  

904
01:33:24,320 --> 01:33:33,080
they're both the same. They both should be 
treated as the same. If you're targeting a  

905
01:33:33,080 --> 01:33:40,240
community and you want them to all adopt 
and get saturation, you need to build  

906
01:33:40,240 --> 01:33:45,360
marketing that shows imagery of that community 
or whatever. And then when you get in the app,  

907
01:33:45,360 --> 01:33:50,600
you have to be able to join that community.
When you invite people from that app,  

908
01:33:50,600 --> 01:33:57,040
that community needs to be mentioned. You need 
to actually cover everything from the ads to the  

909
01:33:57,040 --> 01:34:03,520
in-app experience. All of that needs to be aligned 
for a user acquisition and flywheel to spin. A lot  

910
01:34:03,520 --> 01:34:09,760
of people really screw that up. That's my initial 
rough approximation of what I do when I come in  

911
01:34:09,760 --> 01:34:15,000
and try to fix or try to help with some of 
the challenges these companies are facing.

912
01:34:15,000 --> 01:34:19,280
So this is actually a great segue to the final 
thing I want to make sure people understand is  

913
01:34:19,280 --> 01:34:24,240
you help companies through this. Talk about how 
you work with companies where they can find you,  

914
01:34:24,240 --> 01:34:28,360
what kind of companies you're looking 
to work with and how all that works.

915
01:34:29,120 --> 01:34:36,680
So I work across the gamut. Most of them are 
consumer mobile companies and there certainly  

916
01:34:36,680 --> 01:34:42,800
are web ones too, but I work with companies 
across stages. Typically, I recommend that  

917
01:34:42,800 --> 01:34:49,000
you don't book me unless you're venture backed 
because it's a little expensive. But my main goal  

918
01:34:49,000 --> 01:34:58,560
when someone does seek my advice through intro 
is I try to make them 10 times back their money  

